    <fr:title text="A wild universal cone from a splitting of the generic element">A wild universal cone from a splitting of the generic element</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Construction</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="jms-0037.xml" title="Wild category" addr="jms-0037" type="local">wild category</fr:link>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I:\mathbf {ob}_{\mathcal {C}}]]></fr:tex> be an object of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> such  that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\Delta  I}\xrightarrow {{\alpha }}{1_{\mathcal {C}}}]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="jms-0039.xml" title="Wild natural transformation" addr="jms-0039" type="local">wild natural transformation</fr:link> from the <fr:link href="jms-003D.xml" title="The wild constant functor" addr="jms-003D" type="local">constant 0-functor</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathcal {C}}\xrightarrow {{\Delta  I}}{\mathcal {C}}]]></fr:tex> to the <fr:link href="jms-003C.xml" title="The wild identity functor" addr="jms-003C" type="local">identity 0-functor</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathcal {C}}\xrightarrow {{1_{\mathcal {C}}}}{\mathcal {C}}]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I:\mathbf {ob}_{\mathcal {C}}]]></fr:tex>. Now let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r:\mathbf {hom}_{\mathcal {C}}{\mathopen {}\left (I,J\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s:\mathbf {hom}_{\mathcal {C}}{\mathopen {}\left (J,I\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> be a section-retraction pair witnessed by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\eta  : s;r = 1_{I}]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma  : r;s=\alpha _{I}]]></fr:tex> be a splitting of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{I}:\mathbf {hom}_{\mathcal {C}}{\mathopen {}\left (I,I\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. Then we may define a <fr:link href="jms-0039.xml" title="Wild natural transformation" addr="jms-0039" type="local">wild natural transformation</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\Delta  J}\xrightarrow {{\beta }}{1_{\mathcal {C}}}]]></fr:tex> and an identification <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\chi  : \beta _{J} = 1_{J}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>(This construction is due to <fr:link href="https://homotopytypetheory.org/2018/11/26/impredicative-encodings-part-3/" type="external">Mike Shulman</fr:link>.)</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>3</fr:month><fr:day>14</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>10550</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/5967</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-5967.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>Define the component <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta _{A}:\mathbf {hom}_{\mathcal {C}}{\mathopen {}\left (J,A\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> to be the composite <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s;\alpha _{A}]]></fr:tex>; for the wild naturality structure, we fix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f:\mathbf {hom}_{\mathcal {C}}{\mathopen {}\left (A,B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> to define <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta _{f} : \beta _{A};f = 1_{J};\beta _{B}]]></fr:tex> as follows:</fr:p>

  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {aligned}
    \beta _{A};f & = {\mathopen {}\left (s;\alpha _{A}\right )\mathclose {}};f        \\
                & = s;{\mathopen {}\left (1_{A};\alpha _{B}\right )\mathclose {}}  \\
                & = s;\alpha _{B}                \\
                & = 1_{J}; {\mathopen {}\left (s;\alpha _{B}\right )\mathclose {}} \\
                & = 1_{J}; \beta _{B}
  \end {aligned}
  ]]></fr:tex>


  <fr:p>Next we identify <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta _{J}]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1_{J}]]></fr:tex>. By incoherent naturality, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{J};s = \alpha _{I}]]></fr:tex>; thus by our splitting of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{I}]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{J};s = r;s]]></fr:tex> and hence by postcomposing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex> and canceling via <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\eta :s;r=1_{I}]]></fr:tex> we conclude that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _J = r]]></fr:tex>. Therefore <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta _J=s;\alpha _J=s;r=1_{J}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
